Node reverse(Node head) {

Node prev = null;

while (head != null) {

Node temp = head.next;

head.next = prev;

prev = head;

head = temp;

}

return prev;

}

Classic logic for reversing a singly linked list.

questionContent.body:
What does this DP code solve?

public class Main {

public static int coinChange(int[] coins, int amount) {

int[] dp = new int[amount + 1];

Arrays.fill(dp, amount + 1);

dp[0] = 0;

for (int coin : coins) {

for (int i = coin; i <= amount; i++) {

dp[i] = Math.min(dp[i], 1 + dp[i - coin]);

}

}

return dp[amount] > amount ? -1 : dp[amount];

}

}

solution.name: Solution 1
solution.details:
Answer: B) Minimum number of coins to make amount


Explanation: Classic unbounded knapsack variation, updating dp[i] for minimum coins to reach value i.

graph.get(2).add(0);

dfs(0, visited, graph);

}

}

Explanation: Graph has edges 0‚Üí1‚Üí2‚Üí3. DFS from node 0 reaches all nodes including 3. So visited[3] = true.

public static int kadane(int[] arr) {

int max = arr[0], curr = arr[0];

for (int i = 1; i < arr.length; i++) {

curr = Math.max(arr[i], curr + arr[i]);

max = Math.max(max, curr);

}

return max;

}

Explanation: This is Kadane‚Äôs Algorithm, optimal for finding maximum contiguous sum in O(n) time

Which of the following is not a property of an AVL Tree?

solution.name: Solution 1
solution.details: An AVL Tree is a type of self-balancing Binary Search Tree (BST). It maintains the BST property, meaning the left subtree contains smaller values and the right subtree contains larger values. Additionally, it ensures that the tree remains height balanced by keeping the height difference (balance factor) between the left and right subtrees of any node to at most 1 (i.e., |height(left) - height(right)| ‚â§ 1). This guarantees efficient operations with logarithmic time complexity. However, a B-Tree is a completely different data structure, typically used in databases and file systems for storing large blocks of sorted data. It is not related to AVL Trees, and hence, is not a property of an AVL Tree.

questionContent.body: In which type of binary search tree does an inorder traversal always produce the elements in sorted (non-decreasing) order?

solution.name: Solution 1
solution.details: Inorder traversal of any Binary Search Tree (BST) yields the elements in sorted (non-decreasing) order. This is because a BST maintains the property that for any node, all values in its left subtree are smaller, and all values in its right subtree are larger. This property is preserved in all types of BSTs, including AVL Trees and Red-Black Trees, which are self-balancing versions of BSTs. Therefore, performing an inorder traversal on any of these trees will always produce a sorted sequence of elements. Hence, the correct answer is all of the above.

questionContent.body: In a singly linked list, what is the time complexity of deleting a node when only a pointer to that node is given (and not the head)?

solution.name: Solution 1
solution.details:
Explanation:


If you are given only a pointer/reference to the node to be deleted (and not the head of the singly linked list), you cannot traverse backward, as singly linked lists do not store references to previous nodes.

However, you can still delete the node in O(1) time using a trick:


‚Üí Copy the data from the next node into the current node.


‚Üí Skip the next node by updating the link:


node.data = node.next.data;


node.next = node.next.next;

This effectively removes the next node, and the current node now holds its data, which simulates deletion.


Limitation: This method does not work for the last node, since there is no next node to copy from.
